From: nix-on-z <nix-on-z@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH 1/3] lib/systems/examples: add gcc.arch=z13 for s390x

The s390x cross-compilation target has no GCC architecture flags set,
unlike ARM (armv5t, armv7-a), LoongArch (la64v1.0), and other targets
that specify their minimum architecture level.

Without -march=z13, the cross-compiler defaults to the base z900
instruction set (circa 2000), missing critical hardware features:

  - Vector extensions (SIMD) — z13, 2015
  - Vector enhancements (IEEE 128-bit float) — z14, 2017
  - Miscellaneous instruction extensions — z14+

This causes build failures in packages that detect s390x and try to
use vector intrinsics (e.g., zlib's hardware-accelerated CRC32),
because the builtins require -mvx which -march=z13 implies.

z13 (2015) is a reasonable minimum: it's 10+ years old, and all
currently supported IBM Z hardware (z14, z15, z16, LinuxONE)
is z13 or newer.

diff --git a/lib/systems/examples.nix b/lib/systems/examples.nix
index XXXXXXX..XXXXXXX 100644
--- a/lib/systems/examples.nix
+++ b/lib/systems/examples.nix
@@ -246,6 +246,12 @@

   s390x = {
     config = "s390x-unknown-linux-gnu";
+    gcc = {
+      # z13 (2015) is the minimum for vector extensions (SIMD).
+      # All currently supported IBM Z hardware is z13 or newer.
+      # Enables: -mvx -mzvector (vector facility)
+      arch = "z13";
+    };
   };

   arm-embedded = {
